Information:

The ‘Boschbouwproefstation’ was founded in the year 1913. Numerous forest officers, overseers, rangers, etc., in the employ of the D.E. Indian Forest Service, and some others who were not, have made extensive collections (numbering, amount, etc. see below) on behalf of this Institute.1 

The more important collectors are (names with ‘oe’ will occasionally have been written with ‘u’, but have been inserted here with ‘oe’):

collections:

 

Herb. For. Res. Inst. Buitenzorg [BZF]; duplicates in Herb. Bog. [BO]; partly in Herb. Leiden [L] and Utrecht [U] too.

The oldest collections originally had private numbers only; as far as possible the specimens were provided with F.R.I. numbers later. Subsequent collections were numbered consecutively, those from Java and neighbouring islands with Ja. (= Java) nos, those from other islands of the D.E.I. with bb. (= bossen buitengewesten) nos. In some regions especially complete collections were made, viz in S. Sumatra with E. and T. nos (cf. resp. Endert and Thorenaar); and from numbered trees in Sumatra West Coast with S.W.K. I-III nos, from P. Singkep (Lingga Arch.) with Ri. I nos, from Billiton (Distr. Tandjong Pandan) with Blt. I nos, from SW. Celebes with Cel. I nos, from Centr. Celebes (Malili) with Cel. II-V nos.

The total collections (in Oct. 1942) amounted to: 33128 bb. nos (including 1263 Achmad, 69 Béguin, 662 Brass & Meyer Drees & Versteegh nos which were not collected on behalf of the F.R.I.), 5035 Ja. nos (incl. 64 Backer nos not collected on behalf of the F.R.I.), 1306 E. nos (incl. 110 nos not collected in S. Sumatra), 1317 T. nos, 51 S.W.K. I nos, 30 S.W.K. II nos, 35 S.W.K. III nos, 194 Ri. I nos, 140 Blt. I nos, 96 Cel. I nos, 56 (99-154) Cel. II nos, 301 (200-500) Cel. If nos, 180 Cel.III nos, 115 (80-194) Cel. IV nos, 285 (119-403) Cel. V nos; together upwards of 37000 nos (including upwards of 2000 nos not collected on behalf of the F.R.I.).

These collections, specified as to the various regions of Indonesia, are: Sumatra: Atjeh 724 nos, Tapanoeli 1071 nos, Sumatra West Coast 1671 nos, Sumatra East Coast (incl. Siak and Bengkalis) 2155 nos, Indragiri 1191 nos (incl. 790 Buwalda nos), Djambi 304 nos, Benkoelen 982 nos, Palembang 3359 nos (incl. 90 Buwalda nos), Lampong Districts 420 nos; P. Simaloer 16 nos (excl. Achmad nos); P. Nias 56 nos; P. Morsala 191 nos; Mentawei Islands (P. Siberoet) 78 nos and (N. Pagai) 5 nos; P. Enggano 170 nos (incl. 159 Lütjeharms nos); Banka 472 nos; Billiton 442 nos; Riouw-Lingga Archipelago 931 nos (many on P. Singkep); Java 4900 nos (incl. some from Noesa Kambangan); Trouwers Isl. 24 nos; Noesa Kambangan (cf. sub Java); Kangean Arch. 12 nos; P. Bawean 63 nos (Buwalda); Bali 327 nos; Lombok 64 nos; Soembawa 224 nos; Soemba 83 nos; Flores 422 nos; P. Roti 2 nos; Alor 11 nos; Dutch Timor 354 nos (incl. 75 Bloembergen nos); P. Wetar 123 nos (incl. 110 Bloembergen nos); P. Roma 6 nos; Tanimbar Islands 219 nos (Buwalda); Dutch W. Borneo 2191 nos; S. & SE. Borneo (exc. P. Laoet) 3419 nos (incl. 58 Buwalda nos); Dutch NE. literature:

(la) For papers published by forest officers etc., cf. the journals, ‘Tectona’, ‘Meded. Proefstat. Boschwezen’ and ‘Het Bosch’.

A very useful book was written by Dr F.H. Endert (see there) with keys for the identification of Malaysian trees by means of vegetative characters.

(lb) Numerous typed reports, written in Dutch, are compiled upon the various larger explorations.

(2) cf. Typed reports Th. Kern 1913 in For. Res. Inst.

(3) cf. Typed report by Schnepper on subdiv. Korintji 1924.
